[
    {
        "content": "<p>I've been playing around with metric spaces lately, and it's occurred to me that infinity-metric spaces (i.e. metric spaces in which the distance function is valued in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mrow><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></msup><mo>∪</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb R^{\\geq 0}\\cup \\{\\infty\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">≥</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∪</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span> rather than just <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mrow><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb R^{\\geq 0}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">≥</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>) are potentially more interesting from a categorical perspective than typical metric spaces. For instance, if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Met}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Met</span></span></span></span></span> is the category of metric spaces with distance-non-increasing maps, and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{InfMet}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">InfMet</span></span></span></span></span> is the corresponding category of infinity-metric spaces, then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{InfMet}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">InfMet</span></span></span></span></span> has coproducts whereas <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Met}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Met</span></span></span></span></span> does not.</p>\n<p>Does anyone know if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{InfMet}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">InfMet</span></span></span></span></span> has been studied before? I'd be surprised if it hasn't - but I would appreciate it if someone could point me towards a book/paper/blog post that studies its properties. A cursory googling yields nothing.</p>",
        "id": 281623036,
        "sender_full_name": "Franklin Pezzuti Dyer",
        "timestamp": 1652051418
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes!  Lawvere famously observed that extended (meaning infinite distances are allowed) quasi (meaning the metric need not be symmetric) pseudo (meaning distinct points can be at distance 0) metric spaces are exactly the same as categories enriched over the poset <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[0,\\infty]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>, with the reverse of the usual ordering and addition as the tensor product.  Hence, they have all the good properties that a category of enriched categories has, and moreover operations like Cauchy completion can be identified with categorical ones as well.  The paper is <a href=\"http://tac.mta.ca/tac/reprints/articles/1/tr1abs.html\">Metric spaces, generalized logic and closed categories</a>.</p>",
        "id": 281623725,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1652052493
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In his honor, extended quasi pseudo metric spaces are sometimes called <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Lawvere%20metric%20spaces\">[[Lawvere metric spaces]]</a>.</p>",
        "id": 281623734,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1652052526
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is incredible, I had no idea (and I'm not sure how I would have found out about this otherwise). Thanks so much!</p>",
